If your software can interact with users remotely through a computer
network, you should also make sure that it provides a way for users to
get its source.  For example, if your program is a web application, its
interface could display a "Source" link that leads users to an archive
of the code.  There are many ways you could offer source, and different
solutions will be better for different programs; see section 13 for the
specific requirements.

================================================================================
EKEX INTELLIGENCE â NETWORK SERVICE AMENDMENTS & SOURCE AVAILABILITY NOTICE
================================================================================

In addition to the GNU Affero General Public License v3.0 (AGPL-3.0) terms
above, the following amendments apply specifically to deployments of EKEX
Intelligence as a network service (SaaS, API, bot, or any remote interaction):

1. SOURCE OFFER MECHANISM
   Any deployment of EKEX Intelligence that allows users to interact with
the software remotely through a computer network MUST prominently provide
a mechanism for all such users to obtain the Corresponding Source of the
deployed version, including all modifications, configurations, and
derivative works.

   Acceptable mechanisms include but are not limited to:
   (a) A "Source" link in the user interface footer or navigation;
   (b) An API endpoint at /source or /license returning source access info;
   (c) A message displayed by the NEZA bot (Telegram/WhatsApp) with source URL;
   (d) Documentation prominently linked from all user-facing entry points.

2. CORRESPONDING SOURCE DEFINITION
   For EKEX Intelligence, "Corresponding Source" includes:
   (a) The complete source code of all AGPL-3.0-licensed modules in src/;
   (b) All build scripts, configuration files, and deployment manifests;
   (c) All NEZA intent engine models, weights, and training data (if any);
   (d) All modifications, patches, or custom integrations applied to the core.

3. NO PROPRIETARY WRAPPER CIRCUMVENTION
   Deploying reverse proxies, CDNs, API gateways, or middleware that
obscure, modify, or intercept EKEX API requests/responses WITHOUT
offering Corresponding Source constitutes a direct license violation.
Building a proprietary frontend, mobile app, or wrapper around EKEX
APIs does NOT exempt you from source disclosure obligations for the
underlying EKEX deployment.

4. WHITE-LABEL & MULTI-TENANT DEPLOYMENTS
   White-label, reseller, or multi-tenant deployments MUST provide
source access to ALL end users interacting with the software, not merely
the deploying entity. Each end user's interface MUST contain the source
offer mechanism.

5. NO COMMERCIAL SUBLICENSE
   EKEX Intelligence is licensed under AGPL-3.0 ONLY. No contributor or
deployer may grant proprietary sublicenses, commercial licenses, or
closed-source distribution rights for any code derived from this repository.
Revenue may be generated ONLY through AGPL-3.0-compliant services:
consulting, support, hosting, customization, and deployment assistance.

6. ATTRIBUTION
   All deployments MUST retain the following attribution in user-facing
interfaces and API responses:
   "Powered by EKEX Intelligence â Open Intent Intelligence Infrastructure
    (https://ekexintelligence.com) Â· Licensed under GNU AGPLv3"

7. JURISDICTION
   This license and its amendments are governed by the laws of Rwanda.
Disputes shall be resolved through binding arbitration at the
Kigali International Arbitration Centre (KIAC).

